        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 5:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τοὺς ἁμαρτάνοντας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": It cannot be certainly determined whether this refers to offending presbyters only or to sinners in general. In favour of the first alternative, is the consideration that it seems to be a suitable conclusion to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 5:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; and the vehemence of the adjuration in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 5:21",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " receives thus a justification. It demands greater moral courage to deal judicially with subordinate officials than with the rank and file of a society.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "On the other hand, the sequence of thought in these concluding verses of the chapter is not formal and deliberate. Although it has been shown above that ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 5:17-25",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " form one section, marked by one prominent topic, the relation of Timothy to presbyters, it cannot be maintained that the connexion is indisputably obvious; and the use of the present participle suggests that habitual sinners are under discussion. One is reluctant to suppose that such men would be found amongst the presbyters of the Church.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἐνώπιον πάντων",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ": At first sight this seems opposed to the directions given by our Lord, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 18:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “Shew him his fault between thee and him alone”; but the cases are quite different: Christ is there speaking of the mutual relations of one Christian with another, as brothers in the household of God; here St. Paul is giving directions to a father in God, a Christian ruler, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 4:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 2:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Moreover, as Ell. points out, Christ is speaking of checking the beginning of a sinful state, St. Paul is speaking of persistent sinners.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἵνα καὶ οἱ λοιποὶ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "κ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "λ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".: ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 13:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Them that sin",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] A connecting particle has some authority here but not enough for adoption. The absence need not (see note above) make us think the subject is changed from ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "offending presbyters",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "sinners generally",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". This would require more support from the context than is given, the main thought being still Timothy’s official and personal bearing towards presbyters. The article with the present participle is nearly the equivalent of a substantive. Cf. Winer, § 47, 7. The same article and present participle occur in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 John 3:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where the force of the present is of the utmost importance. ‘It describes a character, “a prevailing habit,” and not primarily an act.’ Bp Westcott. So here, ‘those who are living in sin’ among the presbyters. Bp Wordsworth gives a special character to these sins: ‘He is speaking specially of Presbyters whose sins, particularly in doctrine, are public and notorious. And this exposition is confirmed by the application of the word “sins” to them here and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "1 Timothy 5:24",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "verse-link",
            "text": "1 Timothy 5:24",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 3:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where he says of a heretical teacher that he “sinneth being self-condemned.” St Paul thus declares the moral guilt of false doctrine.’ And he quotes St Paul’s prophecy to the Athenian presbyters of such ‘grievous wolves,’ ‘speaking perverse things’ among them, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Acts 20:29",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "rebuke before all",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] The word is sometimes ‘convict,’ sometimes ‘condemn.’ In its use in these Epistles, here and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Timothy 4:2",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 1:9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 1:13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Titus 2:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", it seems always to have reference to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "false teaching",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and its consequent ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "evil living",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and to unite the sharp convincing proof of the error and the sharp condemning reproof of the vice.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "that others also may fear",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Rather, as R.V., ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "that the rest also may be in fear",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ‘the rest,’ i.e. those who have heard and perhaps approved of the false teaching and its vicious morals; ‘may be in fear,’ the longer expression being used to denote the state of abiding ‘godly fear.’",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Timothy 5:20",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Τοὺς ἁμαρτάνοντας",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "them that sin",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", the elders convicted by witnesses. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "The others",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " are contradistinguished from those.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οἱλοιποὶ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the others",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in the flock, who have either committed the same sin, or lest they should commit it.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "φόβον",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "fear",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") suitable to those who are prepared to sin.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
